Germany : a costly budget fetish
FRANKFURT – The European Central Bank (ECB) is under virulent attacks in Germany, a country that has long prided itself on defending the principle of central bank independence.
Indeed, it was Germany that insisted on incorporating this principle into the criteria outlined by the Maastricht Treaty, which set the conditions for membership in the European Monetary Union.
For many members of the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU), the decision to grant independence to their central bank in order to join the eurozone implied a change in political regime.
Thus, the independence of the Bank of France, during the ratification referendum of the Maastricht Treaty in 1992, was one of the strongest arguments in the campaign against joining the euro.
In today's Germany, it has become commonplace, one might say, to exert pressure on the central bank.
For several months, even the Minister of Finance, Wolfgang Schaüble, has regularly commented on the monetary policy of the European Central Bank (ECB).
Schaüble's interventions target the very core of what constitutes the central bank's independence.
If he does not seek to redefine the objective of monetary policy (this "price stability" standard, in the old jargon of the Bundesbank), he nonetheless provides his advice on the tools the ECB should use and how it should wield them to achieve such a goal.
We have seen precedents.
In 1998, Oskar Lafontaine, then the German Minister of Finance, gave his good advice to the first President of the ECB, Wim Duisenberg, on how to conduct monetary policy (Lafontaine's objective was, in the end, to create a target zone for exchange rates).
Duisenberg, with his typical Dutch laconicism, replied that it was nothing unusual for a politician to express his opinion on monetary policy (in Germany, this was absolutely unusual). "Yet – he added – it would be entirely abnormal to take account of [his] suggestions."

The respect for the independence of monetary policy has long been a central element of the German "Stabilitätkultur" (culture of stability).
The founding act of the reputation for strict independence acquired by the Bundesbank was its refusal to yield to Chancellor Konrad Adenauer's exhortations, who wanted it to contain the rise in interest rates in 1956.
At this time, France did not see things in the same way.
Charles de Gaulle was about to create the Fifth Republic, with a Banque de France that reported to the Minister of Finance.
But it was a different time.
Following the various crises that shook the ECU, monetary policy has increasingly tended to replace fiscal policy.
Had the old doctrine become obsolete?
The Europe remains very vulnerable; the median inhabitant of the EUM has already lost ten years, and, what is even more alarming, we are close to a critical situation.
However, the United States are doing better.
Despite a difficult political deadlock to manage, they have managed to tackle the macroeconomic problem (the weakness of aggregate demand) they were facing by launching expansionary fiscal and monetary policies.
The United States have also better managed their banking problems, which, initially, were far more severe than in Europe.
(There is obviously a strong interaction between the measures that can be taken in both areas.
The more robust an economy is, the more profitable its banks are and the more capable they are of fulfilling their function: financing the economy.
But the independence of the ECB is less threatened by the good advice of a finance minister than by the lack of public support.
In fact, the famous autonomy of the Bundesbank rested less on its legal status than on the unwavering support (justified by its performance) of German citizens.
It is exactly the opposite with the ECB.
Voices are being heard, notably in Germany, calling for it to be subjected to more pressure.
But the greatest threat to the independence of the ECB lies in the unbearable burden that weighs on its shoulders.
The less fiscal policy is called upon to stabilize production, the more central banks are de facto forced to take on this objective (unless, of course, they are designed to let nature take its course, allowing the economy to sink into stagnation, or worse).
The political result of this chain of events is a very clear regression toward nationalism, both left and right, in all countries of theEMU, including Germany.
The rise of nationalism is almost a logical corollary of the policies pursued.
It is endogenous.
And there too, Germany leads the dance, with its obsession with the schwarze Null, budget balance, against all winds and tides.
In Germany, deficits are viewed negatively, not only from an arithmetic point of view, but also morally, even though this defies good economic sense and resembles clientelism.
At the end of the 19th century, the main German specialists in public finance, including Albert Schäffle and Adolph Wagner, formulated a "golden rule" according to which current expenditures must, on average, be financed by current revenues.
Public spending, and the resources it requires, are justified by their utility.
This amounts to saying that investments aimed at improving productivity – equipment expenditures – can be financed with debt, whose service is ensured by the growth of incomes and the base of related revenues.
This classical approach has been institutionalized in a useful concept: the distinction between current expenditures and investment expenditures, which is always practiced at the municipal level in Germany (and Austria).
This is crucial, because in Germany, about 50% of public sector investment expenditures are managed at this level (a proportion that is declining, since the municipal share was two-thirds at the beginning of the 1990s).
These expenditures are consistent with supporting the competitiveness of German small and medium-sized businesses (Mittlestand).
But compared to the beginning of the 1990s and at constant prices, investment expenditures have fallen by about 15%.
More than a decade ago, they have been insufficient to maintain the capital stock.
If this is not the way to prepare for the future, it is the way to undermine productivity and prosperity.
In short, the German austerity goes against the intended goal.
Outdated infrastructure (though not as much as in the United States) has become a real problem for Germany.
Furthermore, the fiscal prudence of German leaders spills over German borders and its effects are amplified by the monetary union, which lacks exchange rates to accommodate national particularities.
Of course, the European monetary union is imperfect.
But turning the only institution ready to « do what is necessary » to bring the ECU back on track into a scapegoat is a very bad idea.
Letting the states use, where it exists, the budgetary space they have at their disposal to relieve pressure on the ECB would be a much better strategy.
Germany, without a doubt, enjoys a certain margin of maneuver in this regard.
